what is the reason to delete this?
It's syntactically a special case of the above
I imagine this was added only to aid the port when Lean wouldnâ€™t automatically infer the correct type. I donâ€™t see a use for this now that things â€œjust work.â€
Yeah I was just confused as it wasn't used anywhere it seems? So why would the porter add it, oh well if it seems useless its good to get rid of it
Does dsimp work with the same trick? I think this proof is easier to maintain if so
Sorry I am confused as to what is being asked here. Swap out `dsimp` for `simp`?
I pushed a `simp? says`. Let me know if you think that is an improvement in this regard. (It also told me I could drop some parens).
The lean3 proof was apparently `dsimp; simp`. I'm suggesting you restore that proof as `dsimp [(foo)]; simp [(bar)]` as appropriate, ideally reaching the same intermediate goal state.
I tried that at first. Let me try again.

Best I can do is 
```lean
dsimp -- does some things 
simp [(add_apply), (comp_apply)]
```
in Lean 3 the `add_apply` and `comp_apply` get called with the `dsimp` leaving only `zero_add` and `add_zero` to clean up but the parens trick doesn't work here with `dsimp`. 

We could also just do 
```lean
simp [(add_apply), (comp_apply)]
```
alone. Thoughts?
I see that your PR about `Algebra.id` was merged recently. Is this workaround still needed?
Unfortunately, yes.
I found the declarations that need to be reducible.
What semireducible definitions need to be unfolded?
Lean doesn't seem to want to unfold `PseudoMetricSpace.toUniformSpace`.

Actually this might be another case of `RingHom.id` not being reducible. See [Simp claims not defeq but rfl works](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/270676-lean4/topic/Simp.20claims.20not.20defeq.20but.20rfl.20works)
No that doesn't help anything.

We end up at 
```lean
 âŒ @Exists =?= PseudoMetricSpace.toUniformSpace.1.1 
```
